<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06274070 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06274070 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FAMILY; COMMUNICATION; TECHNOLOGY; LIFESTYLE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  THE next time you hear the insistent tones of a beeper in a restaurant ortheater, the wearer may be not a doctor or a plumber on call but an expectantfather awaiting word from his wife, a mother needed by her baby sitter orsomeone who just needs to be in touch with a business or home.;   Mark and AmyCollier of St. Louis, Mo., who are expecting a child this month, rented abeeper last week to communicate instantly when they are apart. He's an accountmanager for SmithKline Beecham; she's a teacher.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  A NEW HIGH-TECH APRON STRING FOR PARENTS: THEPERSONAL PAGER  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Mercury News staff writer Richard Scheinin contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;He's always on the road calling on key accounts,&quot; Amy Collier said. &quot;Ourgame plan is that I would call the beeper number wherever I am and he wouldknow it's the time.&quot;;   Beepers, or pagers, have long been used byprofessional and business people. But recently they have been making greaterinroads among consumers who want them for personal or family reasons for onlya short time.;   &quot;Short-term renting is really very limited right now,&quot;' saidJonathan Tarlin, a senior consultant at Economic Management ConsultantsInternational of Washington. &quot;But it has been beginning to penetrate theretail market in the past six months.&quot;;   In Mountain View, Mobilecomm hasbegun to target the non-traditional beeper user. It charges a minimum of $16to rent a beeper for a month or less.;   &quot;Say there's a day care center and achild is ill,&quot; said Rosalind Cook, general manager for the firm. &quot;The mother'sat work and gives the beeper number to the day care center and she can stay intouch. I do it for my kids' school. They have my paging number in case theyever need me. A lot of working moms do it. Usually they start using it andthey wind up keeping it.&quot;;   Mike Kaufman, owner of Page West in Santa Clara,said &quot;baby beepers&quot; are becoming more and more common. &quot;We work with Lamazeinstructors in different hospitals,&quot; she said. &quot;They refer the people to us.It's very popular, California being so transient -- husbands working here orthere, and the roads being what they are. We must get 30 calls a week. I justhad a gal in here who just had a baby and had the beeper for two months andwhose husband works for United Parcel.&quot;;   Page West rents beepers for $20 amonth. Both Page West and Mobilecomm charge additional fees for insurance.;  Good Samaritan Hospital in San Jose has been renting beepers to expectantparents for about three years. The hospital asks for a $75 deposit, fullyrefundable, and then charges $5 rental a week per beeper. It has nearly 50beepers &quot;and we're almost constantly out,&quot; says Gina Fogelstrom,administrative director for women and children services at Good Samaritan. &quot;Wereally feel like it's filling a need because we get a lot of success storieswhen the parents return them. They like to tell where the husband was when hegot beeped.&quot;;   Last month, Metromedia Paging Services, a major provider ofpaging services based in Secaucus, N.J., began testing daily and weekly beeperrentals at 35 supermarkets owned by Schnucks Markets, a Midwestern chain. Theunits rent for $2 to $3.50 a day or $10 to $17.50 a week, depending on themodel.;   &quot;We rent them in every store that has a video department,&quot; saidCraig Schnuck, president of the supermarket chain. &quot;The customer signs arental agreement and shows identification.&quot;;   More than 600 companies aroundthe country, called carriers, offer one or more of four types of beeperservices: tone only, a sound or a vibration; tone and voice, a voice messageof up to 10 seconds; numeric or digital, which displays a phone number tocall; and alphanumeric, which displays a text message of up to 1,000characters.;   About 11 million paging subscribers have bought or rentedbeepers, according to Telocator, a trade association for thepersonal-communications industry. Its surveys show that more than two-thirdsof these devices are used for business.;   &quot;When cellular service wasintroduced, many industry analysts forecast the demise of paging,&quot; said ThomasStroup, president of Telocator. &quot;Instead of replacing paging, cellular servedto raise the market consciousness of the value of mobile communications.Paging is the lowest-cost form of personal communications.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910930  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  727  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, September 30, 199100274070,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>